item.description:
Motivation &amp; Definition Fix a commutative ring $R$. Any ideal $\mf{a}
subgrpeq R$ induces a quotient ring $R/\mf{a}$ that makes $\pi:R\onto R/\mf{a}$ a ring homomorphism. If $\mf{a}
eq R$, then $R/\mf{a}$ might have a simpler structure than $\mf{a}$, say, $R/\mf{a}$ might be an integral domain or a field. Definition. A non-trivial ideal $\mf{a}
subgrp R$ is said to be prime (resp. maximal) if $R/\mf{a}$ is an integral domain (resp. a field). Remark. Note that $\mf{p}$ is prime iff $rs\in\mf{p}$ implies either $r\in\mf{p}$ or $s\in\mf{p}$, which is reminiscent to prime numbers in $\Z$.
